The Yajurveda is the second of thefour Vedas, the basic scriptures ç
of Hinduism. It is said to have emerged out of the southern face of ç
Brahm<193>, the creator. It is also called Adhvaryuveda, since its ç
main use is in the performance of  the  Vedic  sacrifices  wherein  the ç
adhvaryu is the chief priest under whose direct guidance the entire ç
sacrifice is performed. Its mantras are called yajus which are in ç
prose.
Since the ancient times, it has been available in two main streams, ç
the K<216><218><207>a Yajurveda and the <185>ukla Yajurveda.
The popular legend that describes how this came about runs as follows: ç
The sage Vai·amp<193>yana, to whom Vedavy<193>sa had imparted the ç
Yajurveda, once incurred the sin of brahmahaty<193> (the sin of ç
killing a br<193>hma<207>a) due to a serious but technical lapse. ç
Being too old and decrepit to perform the prescribed expiation, he ç
asked his disciples to do it on his behalf which was permitted by ç
the relevant scriptures. Y<193>j<210>avalkya, his best disciple, probably ç
due to the pride of his learning, offered to do it all by himself ç
thereby slighting the  other  disciples.  Angered  by  this behaviour ç
of his, Vai·amp<193>yana ordered him to give back the Veda he had ç
taught and quit.
Y<193>j<210>avalkya then `vomitted' the Veda which was black or dark ç
in colour, and left. The other disciples took the form of tittiri ç
birds (partridges) and consumed it. Since it was dark in colour, it ç
came tobe known as K<216><218><207>a Yajurveda (k<216><218><207>a ç
= dark, black). Since the tittiri birds consumed it, it was also called ç
Taittir<200>ya Sa<221>hit<193>.
Y<193>j<210>avalkya later worshipped the Sun-god and got another version ç
of the same Veda from him, who taught it assuming the form of a horse. ç
Hence this branch came to be known as <185>ukla Yajurveda (·ukla ç
= white, bright) and V<193>jasaney<200> Sa<221>hit<193> (v<193>ji ç
= horse).
Obviously  this  legend  is  highly symbolical which has to be unravelled ç
carefully.
The  following  is  one  plausible explanation: Y<193>j<210>avalkya ç
being the most brilliant of all the students of Vai·am-p<193>yana, ç
had mastered the whole of the Yajurveda. He was now forced to ç
teach it to the other disciples. To the extent he taught it to them ç
and to the extent they learnt it, that part of the Veda slipped out ç
of his memory due to the curse of his guru. After thus losing it, ç
he had to regain it†maybe in another form†by his own tapas or austerities ç
in which he succeeded. He pleased God through meditation on the Sun-form ç
and got it.
